<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06129i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06129i">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06129i"> 129(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> un Celte mell&eacute;&mdash;</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">En visitant, en 1870, avec le prince Napol&eacute;on, les huttes d&apos;un campement de Lapons, pr&egrave;s de Tromsoe, je crus plus d&apos;une fois, dans des types de femmes et d&apos;enfants, dans certains traits, dans certaines habi-tudes, voir ressusciter devant moi mes plus anciens souvenirs. L&apos;id&eacute;e me vint que, dans les temps antiques, il put y avoir des m&eacute;langes entre des branches perdues de la race celtique et les races analogues aux Lapons qui couvraient le sol &agrave; leur arriv&eacute;e. Ma formule ethnique serait de la sorte: &laquo; <mark>Un Celte, m&ecirc;l&eacute;</mark> de Gascon, m&acirc;tin&eacute; de Lapon. &raquo; Une telle formule devrait, je crois, repr&eacute;senter, d&apos;apr&egrave;s les th&eacute;ories des anthropologistes, le comble du cr&eacute;tinisme et de l&apos;imb&eacute;cillit&eacute;; mais ce que l&apos;anthropologie traite de stupidit&eacute; chez les vieilles races incompl&egrave;tes n&apos;est souvent qu&apos;une force extraordinaire d&apos;enthousiasme et d&apos;intuition. [By visiting, in 1870, with the Prince Napoleon, the huts of a camp of Lapps, near Tromsoe, I believed more than once, in types of women and children, in certain traits, in certain study, to resuscitate before me my oldest memories. The idea came to me that in ancient times there could be mixtures between lost branches of the Celtic race and races similar to the Lapps that covered the ground on their arrival. My ethnic formula would be like this: "A Celtic, mixed with Gascon, mixed with Lapland. "Such a formula should, I believe, represent, according to the theories of anthropologists, the height of cretinism and imbecility; but what anthropology treats as stupidity in the old incomplete races is often only an extraordinary force of enthusiasm and intuition. <small> Ernest Renan, <a name="ERSD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ERSD"><cite title="source">Souvenirs d'enfance et de jeunesse</cite></a> (1883) 88</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
